<paragraph blockId="1.[608,718,994,1018]" box="[608,718,994,1018]" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">
(
<figureCitation box="[615,709,994,1018]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[133,170,1622,1641]" captionTargetBox="[137,1155,220,1569]" captionTargetId="figure-71@2.[646,1153,630,1034]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Megaselia confuses n. sp. male: 1 – frons; 2 – palps and proboscis; 3 – right thoracic pleura; 4 – left face of hyopopygium; 5 – right face of hypopygium; 6 – front tarsus; 7 – mid tibia; 8 – hind femur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252134" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252134/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Figs 1–8</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[133,1155,1040,1708]" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">
Diagnosis. (Male). In the keys to British species (
<bibRefCitation author="DISNEY R. H. L." box="[748,890,1040,1065]" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref7257" refString="DISNEY R. H. L. 1989. Scuttle Flies Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects 10 (8): 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplet 133, where neither lead fits. The subsequently described 
<taxonomicName authority="Disney" authorityName="Disney" authorityYear="2015" box="[698,864,1071,1095]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="solii">
<emphasis box="[698,781,1071,1095]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">M. solii</emphasis>
Disney
</taxonomicName>
runs to this couplet and is similar, but its hypopygium differs and it has shorter costal cilia and outermost axillary bristles, a longer hair palisade on the mid tibia and half as many differentiated posterodorsal hairs on the hind tibia. In 
<bibRefCitation author="SCHMITZ H. &amp; DELAGE A." box="[323,622,1163,1187]" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" pagination="638 - 664" refId="ref7540" refString="SCHMITZ H. &amp; DELAGE A. 1974. Phoridae. In: LINDNER E. (ed.), Die Fliegen der palaearktischen Region 4 (33) (Lieferung 301): 638 - 664. Stuttgart, E. Schweizerbart'sche Verlagsbuchhandlung." type="book chapter" year="1974">Schmitz &amp; Delage’s (1974)</bibRefCitation>
keys to Abteiling V it runs to couplet 29, where neither lead fits.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[133,1155,1040,1708]" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">
Male. Frons as 
<figureCitation box="[348,412,1224,1249]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[133,170,1622,1641]" captionTargetBox="[137,1155,220,1569]" captionTargetId="figure-71@2.[646,1153,630,1034]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Megaselia confuses n. sp. male: 1 – frons; 2 – palps and proboscis; 3 – right thoracic pleura; 4 – left face of hyopopygium; 5 – right face of hypopygium; 6 – front tarsus; 7 – mid tibia; 8 – hind femur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252134" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252134/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
and with very dense but very fine microtrichia. Cheek with 2 bristles and jowl with 2 that are a little longer and more robust. The subglobose postpedicels brown, with many pale spots, but without SPS vesicles. Palps and proboscis as 
<figureCitation box="[915,981,1286,1310]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[133,170,1622,1641]" captionTargetBox="[137,1155,220,1569]" captionTargetId="figure-71@2.[646,1153,630,1034]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Megaselia confuses n. sp. male: 1 – frons; 2 – palps and proboscis; 3 – right thoracic pleura; 4 – left face of hyopopygium; 5 – right face of hypopygium; 6 – front tarsus; 7 – mid tibia; 8 – hind femur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252134" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252134/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
. Thorax brown. Three notopleural bristles and mesopleuron with 5–8 hairs (
<figureCitation box="[779,845,1316,1341]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[133,170,1622,1641]" captionTargetBox="[137,1155,220,1569]" captionTargetId="figure-71@2.[646,1153,630,1034]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Megaselia confuses n. sp. male: 1 – frons; 2 – palps and proboscis; 3 – right thoracic pleura; 4 – left face of hyopopygium; 5 – right face of hypopygium; 6 – front tarsus; 7 – mid tibia; 8 – hind femur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252134" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252134/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Scutellum with an anterior pair of hairs and a posterior pair of bristles. Abdominal tergites brown with moderate hairs that are only a little longer at rear of T6. Venter brown, and with hairs on segments 3–6. Hypopygium as 
<figureCitation box="[316,414,1408,1433]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[133,170,1622,1641]" captionTargetBox="[137,1155,220,1569]" captionTargetId="figure-71@2.[646,1153,630,1034]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Megaselia confuses n. sp. male: 1 – frons; 2 – palps and proboscis; 3 – right thoracic pleura; 4 – left face of hyopopygium; 5 – right face of hypopygium; 6 – front tarsus; 7 – mid tibia; 8 – hind femur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252134" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252134/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Figs 4–5</figureCitation>
, the lobe of the right side of the hypandrium being vestigial. Fore tarsus with posterodorsal hair palisade on segments 1–4 and as 
<figureCitation box="[827,894,1439,1463]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[133,170,1622,1641]" captionTargetBox="[137,1155,220,1569]" captionTargetId="figure-71@2.[646,1153,630,1034]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Megaselia confuses n. sp. male: 1 – frons; 2 – palps and proboscis; 3 – right thoracic pleura; 4 – left face of hyopopygium; 5 – right face of hypopygium; 6 – front tarsus; 7 – mid tibia; 8 – hind femur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252134" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252134/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
. Dorsal hair palisade of mid tibia extends only about 0.4 times its length its length (
<figureCitation box="[788,856,1470,1494]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[133,170,1622,1641]" captionTargetBox="[137,1155,220,1569]" captionTargetId="figure-71@2.[646,1153,630,1034]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Megaselia confuses n. sp. male: 1 – frons; 2 – palps and proboscis; 3 – right thoracic pleura; 4 – left face of hyopopygium; 5 – right face of hypopygium; 6 – front tarsus; 7 – mid tibia; 8 – hind femur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252134" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252134/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Hairs below basal half of hind femur shorter than those of anteroventral row of outer half (
<figureCitation box="[836,901,1500,1525]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="2.[133,170,1622,1641]" captionTargetBox="[137,1155,220,1569]" captionTargetId="figure-71@2.[646,1153,630,1034]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1–8. Megaselia confuses n. sp. male: 1 – frons; 2 – palps and proboscis; 3 – right thoracic pleura; 4 – left face of hyopopygium; 5 – right face of hypopygium; 6 – front tarsus; 7 – mid tibia; 8 – hind femur." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252134" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252134/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
). Hind tibia with about two dozen differentiated posterodorsal hairs, without anterodorsals, and spinules of apical combs simple. Wings 
<quantity box="[376,473,1562,1586]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.34" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="1.34">1.34 mm</quantity>
long. Costal index 0.35. Costal ratios 6.3–6.4: 1.8: 1. Costal cilia (of section 3) 
<quantity box="[344,440,1593,1617]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="0.14">0.14 mm</quantity>
long. No hair at base of vein 3. With 2 unequal axillary bristles, the outer being 
<quantity box="[303,399,1624,1648]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="0.12">0.12 mm</quantity>
long. Sc not reaching R1. Thick veins brownish gray, veins 4–6 gray and 7 very pale. Membrane lightly tinged gray (not evident to naked eye when viewed against a white background). Haltere brown.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252134" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6252134" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252134/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="13" startId="2.[133,170,1622,1641]" targetBox="[137,1155,220,1569]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[133,1154,1622,1667]" pageId="2" pageNumber="13">
Figs 1–8. 
<taxonomicName authority="DISNEY &amp; WINQVIST, 2018" authorityName="DISNEY &amp; WINQVIST" authorityYear="2018" box="[220,389,1622,1642]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="confuses" status="n. sp.">
